{"id":"math140-limit_sub210-lc002","cid":"MATH 140","topic":"Limits and Continuity","subtopic":"Limits by substitution","difficulty":2,"license":"CC BY-NC-SA (Numberbender original)","instruction":"The demand function for a product is D(p) = {a}p^2 + {b}p + {d}. Find the limit of demand as price approaches ${c_val}.","params":{"a":{"type":"int","min":-2,"max":-1},"b":{"type":"int","min":3,"max":12},"d":{"type":"int","min":30,"max":120},"c_val":{"type":"int","min":1,"max":4}},"answer_expr":"limit_sub210","steps":["Substitute p = {c_val}: {a}({c_val})^2 + {b}({c_val}) + {d} = {answer_limit_sub210}.","When price is ${c_val}, demand approaches {answer_limit_sub210} units."],"tags":["business-calculus","limits","demand","substitution"]}
